name: The Spotted Cow
comments: Less commonly known folksong that probably originated in the 18th century.  In the song, a man is walking and meets a girl who is looking for her spotted cow.  The man says he has seen her cow and that he will take her to the cow.  The strong implication is that they end up having sex during the search.  Thereafter, when the girl sees this man, she yells at him, "I've lost my spotted cow". The song is collected in the Roud Folk Song Index as number 956.  Thomas Hardy in his 1891 novel "Tess of the d'Urbervilles", has Tess' mother sing this song in Chapter 3.

name: Give Me a Little Old Fashioned Love
Country Gardens
comments: A tune from the Oxfordshire Cotswolds in England, usually played on the accordion or fiddle, to accompany traditional English Morris dancing. Its age is undetermined.  The publication date above refers to its first known appearance in print, in Thomas Walker's "The Quaker's Opera -  As It Is Perform'd at Lee's and Harper's Great Theatrical Booth in Bartholomew-Fair - With the Musick Prefix'd to Each Song".  The tune, which is titled Air XX: Country Garden, is played in Act III carrying a song by Walker called "O Goodman Roger, Hold Your Tongue" in which the character Mrs. Coaxthief scolds her husband. The tune was collected separately by Cecil Sharp in 1906 from William "Merry" Kimber , concertina player for the Headington Quarry Morris, with a three line lyric noted in Sharp's field notes.  Sharp later passed the tune to Percy Grainger , whose piano arrangement was first published by Schirmer in 1918.  In the 1950s, Grainger also arranged the melody for woodwind and full orchestra. Until his death in 1961, Country Gardens sheet music sales generated a great proportion of Grainger's income. In a letter to Sharp he wrote:  "It has proven even more of a success than I had expected, and you will see from the enclosed photocopy that it has broken Schirmer's sales records. I hope you will forgive me if I ask you once again if you will consider sharing the royalty with me.  I feel that it is quite undeserved that I should enjoy the whole of it myself."

name: Концерт для фортепиано с оркестром N° 1
comments: The Piano Concerto No. 1 in B-flat minor, Op. 23, was composed between November 1874 and February 1875. It was revised in the summer of 1879 and again in December 1888. The first version received heavy criticism from Nikolai Rubinstein, Tchaikovsky's desired pianist. Rubinstein later repudiated his previous accusations and became a fervent champion of the work. It is one of the most popular of Tchaikovsky's compositions and among the best known of all piano concertos. it was used as the theme to Orson Welles's famous radio series "The Mercury Theatre on the Air" and it came to be associated with Welles throughout his career. The main theme was also made into a popular song titled "Tonight We Love" by Freddy Martin in 1941.

name: The Boston Burglar
comments: "The Boston Burglar" - possibly an Irish-American version of the British song "Botany Bay" was copyrighted in 1881 by H. J. Wehman (New York) and published by him as both a broadside (no. 480) and in "The Vocalists's Favorite Songster" of 1885. Irish singer Delia Murphy's 1940 recording was widely played on the radio in the U.K. and influenced many of the subsequent cover performances. As such, she is often mistakenly credited as the author of "Boston Burglar". There's an American variant called the Louisville Burglar that tells the same tale but changes the locale. Roscoe Holcomb changed the locale again to Covington (Ky.) in a 1964 recording he called "Born and Raised in Covington".
